<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN381-intro">
      <p type="edition">tiṇaiyum tuṟaiyum avai. karumpūr kiḻāṉai naṉṉākaṉār.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en" type="translation">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div xml:id="PN381">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ūṉu mūṇu muṉaiyi ṉiṉiteṉap</l>
<l>pāliṟ peytavum pākiṟ koṇṭavum</l>
<l>maḷavupu kalantu mellitu paruki</l>
<l>viruntuṟut tāṟṟi yiruntaṉe mākac</l>
<l>ceṉmō perumavem viḻavuṭai nāṭṭeṉa</l>
<l>yāntaṉ ṉaṟiyuna mākat tāṉperi</l>
<l>taṉpuṭai maiyi ṉempiri vañcit</l>
<l>tuṇariyatu koḷāa vākip paḻamūḻttup</l>
<l>payampakar vaṟiyā mayaṅkariṉ mutupāḻp</l>
<l>peyalpey taṉṉa celvat tāṅka</l>
<l>ṇīyā maṉṉar puṟaṅkaṭait tōṉṟic</l>
<l>citāar vaḷpiṟ citarppuṟan taṭāri</l>
<l>yūṉcukir valanta teṇka ṇoṟṟi</l>
<l>viralvicai tavirkku maralaiyil pāṇiyi</l>
<l>ṉilampā ṭakaṟṟal yāvatu pulampoṭu</l>
<l>terumara luyakkamun tīrkkuve mataṉā</l>
<l>lirunilaṅ kūlam pāṟak kōṭai</l>
<l>varumaḻai muḻakkicaik kōṭiya piṉṟaic</l>
<l>cēyai yāyiṉu mivaṇai yāyiṉu</l>
<l>mitaṟkoṇ ṭaṟinai vāḻiyō kiṇaiva</l>
<l>ciṟunaṉi, yoruvaḻip paṭarkeṉ ṟōṉē yentai</l>
<l>yoliveḷ ḷaruvi vēṅkaṭa nāṭa</l>
<l>ṉuṟuvaruñ ciṟuvaru mūḻmā ṟuykku</l>
<l>maṟattuṟai yampiyiṉ māṉa maṟappiṉ</l>
<l>ṟiruṅkō ḷīrāp pūṭkaik</l>
<l>karumpa ṉūraṉ kātal makaṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l> Since he feared separation from us because of possessing</l>
<l> love that is great [for] us, while we knew him, (6f.)</l>
<l corresp="5"> [he] said: “go, great man to our land that as festivals, </l>
<l corresp="3"> drinking softly after having measured [and] mixed </l>
<l corresp="2"> pourings of milk and takings of sugar syrup, </l>
<l corresp="1"> thinking [it] sweet when disinclined for [more] meat and food,” </l>
<l corresp="10"> [and] in that place of wealth that is like rain raining, </l>
<l corresp="9"> in an old [place of] ruin with entangled thickets that did not know of announcing yield </l>
<l corresp="8"> after the fruit rotted, being one that is not taken [although there] in clusters, </l>
<l corresp="11"> after having appeared at the outer gate of kings who do not give </l>
<l corresp="16a-c"> we have [now] ended [our] scorching affliction </l>
<l corresp="15"> along with any loneliness by dispelling poverty </l>
<l corresp="14"> with the flawless beat that regulated the speed of [our] fingers </l>
<l corresp="13"> when pressing the clear eye encircled by meat(?) fibres </l>
<l> of [our] Taṭāri drum whose back scatters ragged straps (12).</l>
<l corresp="16d"> Therefore, </l>
<l> after the west wind has run to the thunder sound </l>
<l> of the coming rain to scatter grains on the vast ground (17f.)</l>
<l corresp="19"> if you be far of if you be near, </l>
<l corresp="20"> take this in [and] know, may you live, o Kiṇai drummer: </l>
<l corresp="21"> he who said may you set out on one way, a little, much(?), is our father </l>
<l corresp="22"> man from the land of the Vēṅkaṭa mountain with sounding white waterfalls, </l>
<l corresp="26"> the beloved son of the may from the town of Karumpaṉ </l>
<l corresp="25"> with the resolution not to carry away big takings </l>
<l corresp="24"> without remembering, like a small boat that remains with virtue </l>
<l corresp="23"> when in turn sent out against those who have [age?] and children. </l>
</lg>
